english:
  title: Royal Edict Denying Kwon Geun's Request for Extended Mourning
  author: Jo Yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have received and carefully considered your memorial requesting to resign from office during your period of mourning. I understand well that attending to your father's funeral rites is the natural duty of a son. Yet when the sovereign's command cannot be fulfilled, my heart grows heavy with shame. For while serving one's parents is filial piety, abandoning one's ruler is not loyalty. To interrupt another's mourning is a necessity born of circumstance—can I not then demand obedience to the throne's command?

    I reflect that I, though unworthy, have ascended to this position of honor. Without wise men at my side, how could I govern? Those who seek loyal ministers must look among filial sons, for this principle has endured through the ages. Yet how few truly master learning and virtue! Is it not so that talent is scarce, and fewer still can hold the brush of authority?

    You, Sir, have distinguished yourself through the teachings of Cheng and Zhu, and the eloquence of Ziyou and Zixia. Your name resounds throughout China, your virtue revered in these Eastern lands. You are worthy to wield the historian's pen and to illuminate the ruler's heart. But misfortune has visited you with loss, making your presence impossible to seek. Who else shall discern the proper rites and music? Who else shall compose our diplomatic words? Three months have already passed—why wait a full year?

    Therefore I appoint you to your former position and command your return to duty. This is not because mourning cannot be observed, but because mourning must sometimes yield to service. When I consider the feelings of a filial son, I lament how brief are the days for serving one's parents. When I consider my own heart, I cannot know how long the days of serving one's ruler must be.

    Though you lack the skills of one who defends against invasion, you possess the wisdom to govern. You have made moral virtue your sacred duty; the art of writing is but its shadow. Yet now you suggest that even in mourning garments, you need not neglect your literary duties. If you maintain both the robes of grief and the work of state, you mingle inauspicious with auspicious—a confusion that brings disorder. If I command one clothed in mourning to perform auspicious duties, I too commit this transgression. The auspicious and inauspicious cannot mix; to blur these boundaries is to invite chaos.

    To shorten mourning and return to service is to transform filial duty into loyalty. To defy command and remain in mourning is neither loyal nor filial. But if you outwardly lay aside the mourning robes while inwardly preserving your sorrow, if you perform the sacrifices with greater devotion and observe all the minor and major rites of completion without fail—then you shall fulfill both filial piety and strengthen our literary traditions.

    I urge you, comply with my wishes and assume your position. Your request cannot be granted. Take heed of this royal instruction.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Cheng and Zhu refer to the Neo-Confucian philosophers Cheng Yi and Zhu Xi, whose teachings formed the orthodox Confucian doctrine during the Joseon period.
  - key: ''
    value: Ziyou and Zixia were celebrated disciples of Confucius known for their eloquence and literary abilities.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'historian's pen' refers to the role of official historian, a position of great authority in recording the realm's affairs.
  - key: ''
    value: The concept of 'transforming filial duty into loyalty' reflects the Confucian hierarchy where loyalty to the ruler takes precedence over extended personal mourning in cases of state necessity.
